│ The bug is an incorrect optimization in `InstCombine` where a comparison of two GEPs with  │
│ the same base pointer is simplified to a comparison of their differing indices. This       │
│ transformation is invalid when pointer arithmetic can wrap around the address space,       │
│ causing two pointers with different offsets to become equal.                               │
│                                                                                            │
│ The reproducer demonstrates this with an 8-bit address space (`p:8:8:8`). The GEPs are:    │
│ 1.  `%gep1 = getelementptr i32, ptr %ptr, i8 %idx1`                                        │
│ 2.  `%gep2 = getelementptr i32, ptr %ptr, i8 %idx2`                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ The element size of `i32` is 4 bytes. With `%idx1 = 0` and `%idx2 = 64`, the offsets are:  │
│ *   `offset1 = 0 * 4 = 0`                                                                  │
│ *   `offset2 = 64 * 4 = 256`                                                               │
│                                                                                            │
│ In an 8-bit address space (size 256 bytes), an offset of 256 wraps around to 0. Thus,      │
│ `%gep1` (`%ptr + 0`) and `%gep2` (`%ptr + 256`) point to the same address, and the `icmp   │
│ eq` should be `true`. The faulty optimization simplifies this to `icmp eq i8 0, i8 64`,    │
│ which is `false`.                                                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ The root cause is in `foldGEPICmp` in                                                      │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCompares.cpp`. The logic that simplifies the   │
│ GEP comparison to an index comparison does not account for potential address space         │
│ wrapping.                                                                                  │
│                                                                                            │
│ My fix addresses this by adding a check before performing the optimization. If the GEPs do │
│ not have the `nsw` (no signed wrap) flag and their differing indices are not constant, we  │
│ must consider the possibility of wrapping. The check determines if the difference in       │
│ offsets could be a multiple of the address space size. This is done by checking if the     │
│ address space size is a multiple of the GEP's element size at the differing index. If it   │
│ is, wrapping is possible, and we conservatively abort the optimization by returning        │
│ `nullptr`. This ensures correctness in cases where pointer arithmetic might wrap.          │
│                                                                                            │
│ Here is the patch:                                                                         │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```diff                                                                                    │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCompares.cpp                              │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCompares.cpp                              │
│ @@ -835,6 +835,31 @@                                                                       │
│               ConstantInt::get(I.getType(), ICmpInst::isTrueWhenEqual(Cond)));             │
│                                                                                            │
│        else if (NumDifferences == 1 && CanFold(NW)) {                                      │
│ +        // If the GEPs don't have `nsw` and the indices are not constant, the             │
│ +        // address calculation can wrap, and we can't just compare the indices.           │
│ +        // This is because `(idx1 - idx2) * element_size` can be a multiple of            │
│ +        // the address space size, making the pointers equal when the indices             │
│ +        // are not.                                                                       │
│ +        if (!NW.hasNoSignedWrap() &&                                                      │
│ +            !(isa<Constant>(GEPLHS->getOperand(DiffOperand)) &&                           │
│ +              isa<Constant>(GEPRHS->getOperand(DiffOperand)))) {                          │
│ +          unsigned PointerSize =                                                          │
│ +              DL.getPointerSizeInBits(GEPLHS->getPointerAddressSpace());                  │
│ +          if (PointerSize > 0 && PointerSize <= 64) {                                     │
│ +            APInt AddressSpaceSize = APInt::getOneBitSet(PointerSize, PointerSize);       │
│ +                                                                                          │
│ +            Type *Ty = GEPLHS->getSourceElementType();                                    │
│ +            for (unsigned i = 1; i < DiffOperand; ++i)                                    │
│ +              Ty = GetElementPtrInst::getTypeAtIndex(Ty, GEPLHS->getOperand(i));          │
│ +                                                                                          │
│ +            // If the element size is a divisor of the address space size, we             │
│ +            // can't do the optimization.                                                 │
│ +            if (DL.isKnownNotZero(Ty) &&                                                  │
│ +                AddressSpaceSize.urem(DL.getTypeAllocSize(Ty)) == 0)                      │
│ +              return nullptr;                                                             │
│ +          }                                                                               │
│ +        }                                                                                 │
│ +                                                                                          │
│          Value *LHSV = GEPLHS->getOperand(DiffOperand);                                    │
│          Value *RHSV = GEPRHS->getOperand(DiffOperand);                                    │
│          return NewICmp(NW, LHSV, RHSV);                                                   │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```                                                                                        │
